ion of four important operas: Glinka's A Life for the Tsar (1836), Serov's Judith (1863), Tchaikovsky's The Maid of Orléans (1881), and Rimsky-Korsakov's The Tsar's Bride (1899). He discusses such issues as the influence of Italian and French opera, the use of foreign subjects, the application of local color, and the adherence to the classics, and considers how these related to a sense of "Russianness." Besides yielding new insights for each of these works, this study offers a fresh perspective on the function of nationalist thought in the nineteenth-century Russian opera world. Rutger Helmers is Assistant Professor in Historical Musicology at the University of Amsterdam and lectures in literary and cultural studies at Radboud University Nijmegen.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aNationalism in music. 0aOperazRussiay19th century. 4aEast European Studies. 4aModern History. 4aMusic. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Opera.2bisacsh  aCosmopolitanism.  aGlinka.  aMusic.  aNationalism.  aNineteenth Century.  aRimsky-Korsakov.  aRussian Opera.  aTchaikovsky.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311143136940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978158046873240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781580468732423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781580468732/original  a978-3-11-143136-9  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles